---
import { getEntry } from 'astro:content';
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Lightbox from '../../components/Lightbox.astro';

const entry = await getEntry('projects', 'active-light-cloud');
if (!entry) throw new Error('active-light-cloud project missing');
const { data } = entry;

// Pull supporting images by importing — same files referenced in the markdown body
const studio = (await import('../../content/projects/_assets/active-light-cloud-studio.jpg')).default;
const diagram = (await import('../../content/projects/_assets/active-light-cloud-diagram.png')).default;
const structure = (await import('../../content/projects/_assets/active-light-cloud-structure.jpg')).default;
const milan = (await import('../../content/projects/_assets/active-light-cloud-milan.jpg')).default;
const render = (await import('../../content/projects/_assets/active-light-cloud-render.jpg')).default;
---
<Layout title="MOCKUP: NYT longform — Active Light Cloud" description="Layout mockup using NYT Snow Fall pattern.">
  <p class="mockup-banner">
    <strong>MOCKUP — Pattern 3: NYT longform / Snow Fall.</strong>
    Full-viewport hero, narrow text column (560px), images break to viewport edge.
    <a href="/mockups/pentagram/">Compare with Pattern 4 →</a> · <a href="/projects/active-light-cloud/">Current layout →</a>
  </p>

  <article class="nyt">
    <header class="nyt-hero">
      {data.heroImage && (
        <Image
          src={data.heroImage}
          alt={data.heroImageAlt ?? ''}
          widths={[720, 1080, 1620, 2400]}
          sizes="100vw"
          loading="eager"
          class="nyt-hero-image"
        />
      )}
      <div class="nyt-hero-overlay">
        <p class="nyt-hero-eyebrow">{data.dateDisplay} · {data.partners.join(' · ')}</p>
        <h1 class="nyt-hero-title">{data.title}</h1>
        <p class="nyt-hero-subtitle">{data.subtitle}</p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="nyt-body">
      <p class="nyt-lede"><span class="nyt-dropcap">A</span>ctive Light Cloud was a gesture-responsive lighting system that used advanced computer vision — developed in OpenFrameworks — to predict a user's particular lighting needs through movement. Users could throw light down a dark hallway or bring a cluster of task light to themselves with a single gesture. The conventional ceiling-grid lighting array, that fixed and uniform piece of architectural infrastructure, was reimagined as a medium for spatial dialogue.</p>

      <figure class="nyt-bleed">
        <Image src={studio} alt="Active Light Cloud installation in the GFRY Studio" widths={[1080, 1620, 2400]} sizes="100vw" />
        <figcaption>Installation at the GFRY Studio, School of the Art Institute of Chicago.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>The work began as my MFA thesis at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago's Department of Architecture, Interior Architecture, and Designed Objects (AIADO), under thesis advisor Anders Nereim. The system tracked bodies moving beneath the array using overhead computer vision and rendered the tracking data into a fluid simulation that, in turn, drove the lighting in real time.</p>

      <blockquote class="nyt-pullquote">It was a set of questions about energy, attention, ambient intelligence, and what happens when an architectural surface is given the means to respond.</blockquote>

      <p>Those questions would shape much of my later practice across responsive architecture and experiential media — and continue, in different form, in the work I'm doing now on decision quality and AI-assisted decision coaching.</p>

      <figure class="nyt-bleed">
        <Image src={structure} alt="Close-up of the structural lighting array" widths={[1080, 1620, 2400]} sizes="100vw" />
        <figcaption>Close-up: structural detail of the lighting array.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>The thesis received the AIADO MFA Award of Academic Excellence (2010). The work was presented at the 2009 ACADIA Annual Conference at the Art Institute of Chicago, and at <em>The Bauhaus — From Laboratory to Project</em> international conference at Bauhaus-Universität Weimar.</p>

      <figure class="nyt-bleed">
        <Image src={milan} alt="Active Light Cloud at 2000 Watt Living, Milan, 2010" widths={[1080, 1620, 2400]} sizes="100vw" />
        <figcaption>2000 Watt Living, Fabrica del Vapore, Milan, 2010 — concurrent with Salone Internazionale del Mobile.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>It was subsequently exhibited as part of the GFRY Design Studio's <em>2000 Watt Living</em> exhibitions in Chicago (Sullivan Galleries, 2010) and Milan (Fabrica del Vapore, 2010, concurrent with Salone Internazionale del Mobile / Milan Design Week).</p>
    </div>

    <Lightbox />
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .mockup-banner {
    background: var(--accent);
    color: var(--paper-light);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-5);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--type-sm);
    text-align: center;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .mockup-banner a {
    color: var(--paper-light);
    text-decoration: underline;
    margin-left: var(--space-3);
  }

  .nyt {
    --measure: 36rem; /* ~576px, NYT-narrow */
  }

  /* ----- Hero: full viewport ----- */
  .nyt-hero {
    position: relative;
    height: 90vh;
    min-height: 600px;
    overflow: hidden;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
  }
  .nyt-hero :global(.nyt-hero-image) {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
  }
  .nyt-hero-overlay {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: flex-end;
    padding: var(--space-9) var(--space-7);
    background: linear-gradient(
      to top,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7) 0%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 40%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 70%
    );
    color: white;
    max-width: 80ch;
  }
  .nyt-hero-eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--type-sm);
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    opacity: 0.85;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }
  .nyt-hero-title {
    font-size: clamp(3rem, 6vw, 5.5rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1.05;
  }
  .nyt-hero-subtitle {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--type-h3);
    font-weight: 400;
    line-height: 1.3;
    opacity: 0.95;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  /* ----- Body ----- */
  .nyt-body {
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding: 0 var(--space-5) var(--space-9);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }
  .nyt-body p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
  }

  .nyt-lede {
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  .nyt-dropcap {
    float: left;
    font-size: 4.5rem;
    line-height: 0.9;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin: 0.1em 0.12em 0 0;
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .nyt-pullquote {
    border-left: 0;
    margin: var(--space-7) 0;
    padding: 0;
    font-size: 1.7rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--accent);
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  /* ----- Full-bleed images: extend to viewport edges ----- */
  .nyt-bleed {
    position: relative;
    width: 100vw;
    left: 50%;
    right: 50%;
    margin-left: -50vw;
    margin-right: -50vw;
    margin-block: var(--space-8);
  }
  .nyt-bleed :global(img) {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }
  .nyt-bleed figcaption {
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin: var(--space-3) auto 0;
    padding: 0 var(--space-5);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--type-sm);
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
</style>
